Economist Dawie Roodt has warned that the South African economy will remain uncertain for the foreseeable future. This after the country’s recession deepened in the first quarter of 2020.  [Thread]
The South African economy recorded its third consecutive quarter of economic decline, falling by 2,0% in Q1:2020.#StatsSA #GDP #economy pic.twitter.com/ahJRFtCkTF — Stats SA (@StatsSA) June 30, 2020  Official data released on Tuesday, showed that gross domestic product (GDP) contracted 2% from the previous three months, led by declines in mining and manufacturing. The economy was already frail before the coronavirus pandemic hit South Africa in March, with January-March being the third consecutive quarter of contraction and following a 1.4% decline in GDP in October-December. The latest data nevertheless beat analysts’ expectations for a contraction of 3.8 in the first quarter. Below is the full report from StatsSA:  DV.load("https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/6960606-Gross-Domestic-Product-GDP-1st-Quarter-2020.js", {
